The pages are generally marked across with horizontal ruled lines drawn by a sharp inst-rumcnt', and the columns are defined by perpendicular lines of the same kind, always leaving the column on the left narrower than that on the right. The volume is probably in the original binding: the sides are beech-wood‚ greatly worm-eamn, covered with calf-skin3 the sewing of the back is very rude and cnrious, and the front was formerly secured by clasps.

A very remarkable feature of this manuscript is the copy of the Lord's Prayer, written on the last page, if not by the same hand, at least by one of the same age and school.
